<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="../AOML/AOML.xsl"?>

<observation-set xmlns="http://vortex.cis.vtc.edu/xml/AOML_0.0"
  xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
  xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
  xsi:schemaLocation="http://vortex.cis.vtc.edu/xml/AOML_0.0 ../AOML/AOML.xsd">

  <datetimerange>
    <start resolution="PT05M">
      <ISO>2003-07-10T02:48:00Z</ISO>
    </start>
    <end resolution="PT05M">
      <ISO>2003-07-10T03:40:00Z</ISO>
    </end>
  </datetimerange>
  <location>
    <value>
      <lat-long-alt>+43.00-072.50+300</lat-long-alt>
    </value>
    <notes>
      <xhtml:p>US-Vermont-Tunbridge</xhtml:p>
    </notes>
  </location>
  <observer>Peter C. Chapin</observer>
  <equipment>
    <notes>
      <xhtml:p>75mm Unitron refractor with 25mm (48x), 18mm (67x), 12.5mm (96x), and 9mm (133x)
        eyepieces. I also used Celestron 10x60 binoculars to help locate objects.</xhtml:p>
    </notes>
  </equipment>
  <notes>
    <xhtml:p>My plan for the evening was to observe doubles in western Cyg and to catch up on X
      Cyg and W Her.</xhtml:p>
  </notes>

  <observation>
    <object xsi:type="starMultipleObjectType">
      <id catalog="ADS" id="12169"/>
      <type>star/multiple</type>
      <position>
        <equatorial right-ascension="19h10.8m" declination="+49d46m" equinox="B1950.0"/>
      </position>
      <constellation>Cyg</constellation>
      <component designation="A">
        <magnitude>6.84</magnitude>
      </component>
      <component designation="B">
        <magnitude>6.62</magnitude>
      </component>
      <separation designation-1="A" designation-2="B" distance="8.7"/>
    </object>
    <notes>
      <xhtml:p>This double was a little tricky to find because it is somewhat far from any good
        landmarks. I found it easiest to locate by working from the "wing" of Cyg.</xhtml:p>

      <xhtml:p>The double was easily split with the 25mm eyepiece although the components were
        rather close at that low magnification. The components were about equal brightness and
        with much glare. The view with the 18mm eyepiece was particularly satisfying. Nice
        pair.</xhtml:p>
    </notes>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <object xsi:type="starMultipleObjectType">
      <id catalog="ADS" id="12815"/>
      <name>16 Cyg</name>
      <type>star/multiple</type>
      <position>
        <equatorial right-ascension="19h40.5m" declination="+50d24m" equinox="B1950.0"/>
      </position>
      <constellation>Cyg</constellation>
      <component designation="A">
        <magnitude>6.26</magnitude>
      </component>
      <component designation="B">
        <magnitude>6.37</magnitude>
      </component>
      <separation designation-1="A" designation-2="B" distance="39.0"/>
    </object>
    <notes>
      <xhtml:p>This double was nearby ADS-12169. It was very wide and easy. In fact, the double
        was so wide and the star background was so rich that the pair did not seem all that
        interesting. I noticed that the double was resolvable in the finder 'scope at
        8x.</xhtml:p>

      <xhtml:p>The variable R Cyg is near this double and I noticed that it seemed near maximum
        tonight.</xhtml:p>
    </notes>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <object xsi:type="starMultipleObjectType">
      <id catalog="ADS" id="12880"/>
      <name>&delta; Cyg</name>
      <type>star/multiple</type>
      <constellation>Cyg</constellation>
      <component designation="A">
        <magnitude>3.0</magnitude>
      </component>
      <component designation="B">
        <magnitude>6.5</magnitude>
      </component>
      <separation designation-1="A" designation-2="B" distance="2.1" PA="246"/>
    </object>
    <notes>
      <xhtml:p>I was unable to resolve this double due, no doubt, to the brightness of the
        primary. I tried all my eyepieces from the 25mm to the 9mm without any conclusive
        sighting of the secondary. However I did see a <xhtml:em>possible</xhtml:em> glimpse of
        the secondary at a position angle of around 250 degrees. After coming in from outside I
        checked my catalog information and found that the actual position angle is quite close
        to what I was seeing. However, despite that, I can't honestly say that I observed the
        secondary for sure. The view I got was too inferior.</xhtml:p>

      <xhtml:p>Seeing tonight was decent, but not wonderful. It might be good to check this
        double again under conditions of excellent seeing.</xhtml:p>
    </notes>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <object xsi:type="starMultipleObjectType">
      <id catalog="ADS" id="12893"/>
      <type>star/multiple</type>
      <position>
        <equatorial right-ascension="19h43.8m" declination="+35d58m" equinox="B1950.0"/>
      </position>
      <constellation>Cyg</constellation>
      <component designation="A">
        <magnitude>6.50</magnitude>
      </component>
      <component designation="B">
        <magnitude>7.10</magnitude>
      </component>
      <separation designation-1="A" designation-2="B" distance="15.1"/>
    </object>
    <notes>
      <xhtml:p>Easily resolved with the 25mm eyepiece. The difference in brightness between the
        components is noticeable but not extreme. The field of view was interesting. It had a
        lot of faint and mediumly bright stars without being overwhelming. This was a satisfying
        double.</xhtml:p>
    </notes>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <object xsi:type="starMultipleObjectType">
      <id catalog="ADS" id="12900"/>
      <type>star/multiple</type>
      <position>
        <equatorial right-ascension="19h44.0m" declination="+34d53m" equinox="B1950.0"/>
      </position>
      <constellation>Cyg</constellation>
      <component designation="A">
        <magnitude>6.23</magnitude>
      </component>
      <component designation="B">
        <magnitude>8.4</magnitude>
      </component>
      <separation designation-1="A" designation-2="B" distance="38"/>
    </object>
    <notes>
      <xhtml:p>This double was quite wide. The secondary is significantly fainter than the
        primary. The field is rich and that, together with the wide separation, makes this
        double relatively uninteresting.</xhtml:p>
    </notes>
  </observation>

  <observation>
    <object xsi:type="starMultipleObjectType">
      <id catalog="ADS" id="12913"/>
      <name>17 Cyg</name>
      <type>star/multiple</type>
      <constellation>Cyg</constellation>
      <component designation="A">
        <magnitude>5.03</magnitude>
      </component>
      <component designation="B">
        <magnitude>8.5</magnitude>
      </component>
      <separation designation-1="A" designation-2="B" distance="25.9"/>
    </object>
    <notes>
      <xhtml:p>Although this double was also widely separated I found it much more interesting
        than ADS-12900. The primary seemed bright in the 25mm eyepiece with a significantly
        fainter secondary. It was easily resolved, however. The field was very rich and
        interesting.</xhtml:p>
    </notes>
  </observation>

</observation-set>
